Now, moving on to the \(y\) terms. We have \(y^2 + 4y\). Similarly, I need to complete the square here. Half of 4 is 2, and squaring that gives me 4. So, \(y^2 + 4y\) can be rewritten as \((y + 2)^2 - 4\). Again, expanding the square gives me \(y^2 + 4y + 4\), so we subtract 4 to keep the expression equivalent.

